    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3231394673" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3231394673" />
    <a title="David Sarkies" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5856247-david-sarkies"><img alt="David Sarkies" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1470027282p2/5856247.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3231394673?book_show_action=true">Mar 23, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David Sarkies" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David Sarkies" href="/user/show/5856247-david-sarkies">David Sarkies</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780575094161" href="/book/show/6576785-i-am-legend">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5856247-david-sarkies?shelf=horror">horror</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3231394673" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8149964283946807432"><b>The Last Human</b><br/>23 March 2020<br/><br/>	I first heard about this book because somebody decided to make a movie with the same title with Will Smith as the lead role. Well, when I saw the trailers I certainly felt that it looked quite interesting, especially since he seemed to be driving around a completely empty New York City. In fact, I sort of wonder whether that is what New York City is like these days. Melbourne certainly does seem to be much emptier than usual, and while I sort of would like to catch a </span>
  <span id="freeText8149964283946807432" style="display:none"><b>The Last Human</b><br />23 March 2020<br /><br />	I first heard about this book because somebody decided to make a movie with the same title with Will Smith as the lead role. Well, when I saw the trailers I certainly felt that it looked quite interesting, especially since he seemed to be driving around a completely empty New York City. In fact, I sort of wonder whether that is what New York City is like these days. Melbourne certainly does seem to be much emptier than usual, and while I sort of would like to catch a train into town just to look around, a part of me feels that maybe staying at home is a much better option (though I am sure to do that sooner or later, even if only to do some grocery shopping – if I can find any groceries).<br /><br />	Yeah, this seemed to be a rather ironic book to start reading in this day and age, with a disease ravaging the Earth and people literally hunkering down in their homes, with pretty much everything but the essential services being shut. Mind you, this wasn’t quite what I expected when I put this book on the stack of the books that I was going to read, and furthermore, I think I put it on that stack something like three months ago (which sort of indicates how big that stack happens to be, not that I have read a huge number of books over that time, and since I am still doing university, albeit remotely, I doubt I’ll be able to get through many more).<br /><br />	One thing that struck me, not from this book, but from the lighthearted banter that is flying across social media, is a list of movies that one can watch during a pandemic. Anyway, I probably don’t have to write a list of books here, namely because <a href="https://www.capecodtimes.com/entertainmentlife/20200322/books-about-pandemics-to-read-in-time-of-coronavirus" rel="nofollow noopener">The Cape Cod Times</a> and <a href="https://time.com/5807460/books-to-read-coronavirus/" rel="nofollow noopener">Time Magazine</a> have already done that for me. I did notice that <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/51799.The_Decameron" title="The Decameron by Giovanni Boccaccio" rel="nofollow noopener">The Decameron</a> appeared on one of the lists, but I’d also add <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/447383.The_Alchemist" title="The Alchemist by Ben Jonson" rel="nofollow noopener">The Alchemist</a> by <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/22583.Ben_Jonson" title="Ben Jonson" rel="nofollow noopener">Ben Jonson</a>.<br /><br />	Anyway, I’m sure you want to know more about the book than about something that pretty much everybody knows about because there is only one thing that the news cycle seems to be playing today, and that is this book. Well, if you have seen the films that have been based on this book, then you probably know about this book anyway. So, we have this guy who is the only survivor after a plague pretty much turns humanity into a pack of bloodthirsty vampires.<br /><br />	Well, sort of, and not quite, if the end of the book is anything to go by. I guess the thing that stuck in my mind is how <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/search/search?q=Zizek" title="Zizek" rel="nofollow noopener">Zizek</a> suggests how the whole concept of the book has been changed over the years to completely turn away from the original premise. For instance, the ‘I Am Legend’ idea that comes from the recent film is that Robert Neville is the legend of the title because he discovers the vaccine to stop the virus in its tracks (vaccines don’t cure a virus, they just prevent us from being able to contract it, or at least help us build up our immunity to it). However, in this book, the ‘I Am Legend’ title refers to the fact that he is the last human in existence, and once he has passed on, then the whole concept of humanity will be little more than a legend.<br /><br />	In a way, this book is about change, and in a way, it is about social change. Sure, Matheson uses the idea of a horde of vampires taking over the world, but in another sense, it is about how one way of life is slowly subsumed by the other. Take for instance the idea of the First Nations of the Americas. When Europeans arrived there was a thriving society but over the years they were slowly, and surely, completely wiped out. All that remains are small pockets of individuals on reservations killing themselves with alcohol. In turn, the whole concept of these societies has simply been turned into a marketing spin that doesn’t reflect the actual society in which these people once lived.<br /><br />	This is also the case here in Australia, and is especially true when you wander through Sydney. The reality was that there were over a thousand nations living on this continent, but the First Nations here have simply been reduced to people playing digeridoos, and making boomerangs. In fact, they have also been relegated to the idea of unsophisticated hunter-gatherers who needed European assistance to be able to advance, not that we did all that much in the first place. In fact, many of the First Nations people have simply been subsumed into our society, and their culture has been completely lost.<br /><br />	So, yes, this is actually a confronting book, that exposes the nature of how humanity has the ability to simply wipe out and destroy cultures, sending them into the realm of legend. Even though we do have anthropologists that attempt to study, and learn about these cultures, the reality is that for the most part, we don’t see the truth, but rather a sanitised idea of Wigwams, Boomerangs, and pyramids in the jungles.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8149964283946807432" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


